1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:14,080
 [Music]

2
00:00:14,080 --> 00:00:16,560
 Hello, this is Maria from dresspapandmaking.com.

3
00:00:16,560 --> 00:00:19,920
 In this video I'm going to walk you through how to draft the sleeve block.

4
00:00:19,920 --> 00:00:25,120
 You will need to have your bodice block front and back completed before you can draft the sleeve

5
00:00:25,120 --> 00:00:28,800
 as we need the armhole measurements from those blocks.

6
00:00:28,800 --> 00:00:32,600
 On the left is what the sleeve block will look like when I have finished drafting it.

7
00:00:32,600 --> 00:00:35,680
 I will be using standard measurements to draft this block.

8
00:00:35,680 --> 00:00:40,080
 On the right in orange is the bodice front and back, which would complete this block set.

9
00:00:40,080 --> 00:00:44,000
 I have already created the videos for bodice front and back instructions.

10
00:00:44,000 --> 00:00:49,280
 Note that this is the basic one-piece sleeve and it has a dart in the elbow.

11
00:00:49,280 --> 00:00:53,040
 The green sleeve block on the right is my block, which as you may be able to see

12
00:00:53,040 --> 00:00:55,760
 is a bit different in shape to the standard block on the left.

13
00:00:55,760 --> 00:00:59,040
 If you are using your own individual measurements to draft your own custom block

14
00:00:59,040 --> 00:01:02,640
 it may look a little different or significantly different to the one that I'm drafting.

15
00:01:02,640 --> 00:01:07,120
 I actually want to cover a few things before we start drafting the sleeve block.

16
00:01:07,120 --> 00:01:10,880
 Firstly, I want to talk about the seven measurements you need to draft this sleeve block.

17
00:01:10,880 --> 00:01:15,760
 The first measurement is the length of the sleeve from the shoulder tip to the wrist with the arm bent.

18
00:01:15,760 --> 00:01:18,880
 The second measurement is from the shoulder tip to the elbow,

19
00:01:18,880 --> 00:01:21,600
 the third around the elbow with the arm bent.

20
00:01:21,600 --> 00:01:24,480
 These three measurements are fairly straightforward.

21
00:01:24,480 --> 00:01:27,520
 If your sleeve ends up short it's obvious and you add some length.

22
00:01:27,520 --> 00:01:31,440
 If it ends up too tight in the elbow when you bend your arm you add to the elbow width.

23
00:01:31,440 --> 00:01:36,560
 The other four measurements needed to draft the sleeve are the front armhole measurement

24
00:01:36,560 --> 00:01:41,280
 from your front bodice block, the back armhole measurement from your back bodice block,

25
00:01:41,280 --> 00:01:45,280
 the bicep measurement, which is around your bicep at the armhole level

26
00:01:45,280 --> 00:01:48,240
 and the cap height from the shoulder tip to the bicep level.

27
00:01:48,240 --> 00:01:52,560
 Now these four measurements are the building blocks of the sleeve cap.

28
00:01:52,560 --> 00:01:55,280
 Taking these four measurements aren't necessarily difficult,

29
00:01:55,280 --> 00:01:59,520
 except maybe the cap height can be because it's not necessarily that obvious,

30
00:01:59,520 --> 00:02:02,560
 but it is the relationship between these four measurements

31
00:02:02,560 --> 00:02:08,080
 that cause the most problem in drafting a well fitting one-piece fitted sleeve block.

32
00:02:08,080 --> 00:02:11,920
 So let's first look at the definition of a fitted sleeve.

33
00:02:11,920 --> 00:02:14,800
 There are two aspects to the fitted sleeve.

34
00:02:14,800 --> 00:02:19,920
 The first one is the look, it follows the contours of the arm rather than flaring out.

35
00:02:19,920 --> 00:02:24,160
 Minimal ease is added to the bicep to accommodate the arm in a close fit.

36
00:02:24,160 --> 00:02:27,680
 The second aspect is the smooth head of the sleeve,

37
00:02:27,680 --> 00:02:30,320
 so it also has minimal ease in the cap.

38
00:02:30,320 --> 00:02:32,480
 It means there are no tucks and gathers.

39
00:02:32,480 --> 00:02:36,400
 Only enough ease is put in to sew the sleeve into the curve of the armhole.

40
00:02:36,400 --> 00:02:40,400
 So in the graphics shown, only A is a fitted sleeve,

41
00:02:40,400 --> 00:02:43,520
 B has gathers in the sleeve cap, C flares out,

42
00:02:43,520 --> 00:02:47,440
 D and E have gathers either or both in the bicep and the cap.

43
00:02:48,080 --> 00:02:50,320
 Now, as I've said, the key for a fitted sleeve

44
00:02:50,320 --> 00:02:53,760
 is having minimal ease in both the cap and the bicep.

45
00:02:53,760 --> 00:02:56,720
 Now let's go back and have another look at the four measurements

46
00:02:56,720 --> 00:02:59,040
 that we use to draft the sleeve cap.

47
00:02:59,040 --> 00:03:00,960
 If you look at the graphic at the top right,

48
00:03:00,960 --> 00:03:04,000
 you can see that the sleeve curve is built around a triangle.

49
00:03:04,000 --> 00:03:06,720
 The three sides of the triangle are the back armhole,

50
00:03:06,720 --> 00:03:08,560
 the front armhole and the bicep.

51
00:03:08,560 --> 00:03:10,720
 The height of the triangle is the cap height.

52
00:03:10,720 --> 00:03:14,160
 Now I have just enlarged the sleeve cap,

53
00:03:14,160 --> 00:03:15,840
 so we can focus on the triangle,

54
00:03:15,840 --> 00:03:18,160
 but I have not enlarged the inch grid,

55
00:03:18,160 --> 00:03:20,160
 so the sleeve is not in proportion to the grid.

56
00:03:20,160 --> 00:03:24,080
 The sleeve cap is shown by the black curved outline.

57
00:03:24,080 --> 00:03:26,720
 The curve is built, as I said in the last slide,

58
00:03:26,720 --> 00:03:29,040
 upon the triangle underneath.

59
00:03:29,040 --> 00:03:30,880
 Now it should be obvious when you think about it,

60
00:03:30,880 --> 00:03:34,720
 that you cannot draw this triangle using four measurements.

61
00:03:34,720 --> 00:03:37,280
 There are actually three different combinations of these measurements

62
00:03:37,280 --> 00:03:39,600
 that you could use to draw this triangle.

63
00:03:39,600 --> 00:03:43,280
 Firstly, the back armhole, the front armhole and the bicep.

64
00:03:43,280 --> 00:03:47,200
 Secondly, the back armhole, the front armhole and the cap height.

65
00:03:47,200 --> 00:03:49,680
 Or thirdly, the bicep and the cap height.

66
00:03:49,680 --> 00:03:52,720
 Now if you have a standard figure, or if you're lucky,

67
00:03:52,720 --> 00:03:55,040
 the relationship between the cap height and the bicep

68
00:03:55,040 --> 00:03:59,280
 just happened to magically work together to give you the right result.

69
00:03:59,280 --> 00:04:01,040
 But if you're unlucky, it doesn't.

70
00:04:01,040 --> 00:04:04,080
 Now on the left hand side, in example A,

71
00:04:04,080 --> 00:04:06,400
 you have a triangle created with the three measurements

72
00:04:06,400 --> 00:04:09,200
 back armhole, front armhole and bicep.

73
00:04:09,200 --> 00:04:12,320
 In this case, in figure A, the cap height is what it is.

74
00:04:13,120 --> 00:04:15,680
 Now if this was actually your back armhole measurement,

75
00:04:15,680 --> 00:04:18,080
 your front armhole measurement and your bicep,

76
00:04:18,080 --> 00:04:19,760
 all including some E's,

77
00:04:19,760 --> 00:04:24,000
 but the cap height did not match the cap height on your body,

78
00:04:24,000 --> 00:04:25,520
 well what would that mean?

79
00:04:25,520 --> 00:04:29,120
 Well firstly, if that cap height was longer than your cap height,

80
00:04:29,120 --> 00:04:31,680
 and so you had to reduce that cap height,

81
00:04:31,680 --> 00:04:34,240
 you would have to extend the bicep,

82
00:04:34,240 --> 00:04:37,600
 make that bicep larger and have more ease in the bicep.

83
00:04:37,600 --> 00:04:41,280
 Otherwise, you wouldn't have enough room in that curve

84
00:04:41,280 --> 00:04:42,720
 to sew it into the armhole.

85
00:04:42,720 --> 00:04:46,080
 On the other hand, if this cap height was too low

86
00:04:46,080 --> 00:04:48,160
 and you needed a higher cap height,

87
00:04:48,160 --> 00:04:52,080
 you would have to make the back and front armhole lines longer,

88
00:04:52,080 --> 00:04:54,160
 and in that case you'll have more ease

89
00:04:54,160 --> 00:04:57,760
 than you need for a fitted sleeve in the sleeve cap.

90
00:04:57,760 --> 00:04:59,600
 So you would either have to have gathers

91
00:04:59,600 --> 00:05:02,000
 or you could put a dart in the sleeve cap.

92
00:05:02,000 --> 00:05:04,480
 On the right, in example B,

93
00:05:04,480 --> 00:05:06,880
 the triangle is created using the cap height

94
00:05:06,880 --> 00:05:09,200
 and the front and back armhole measurements.

95
00:05:09,200 --> 00:05:11,520
 Again, if this was your back armhole measurement,

96
00:05:11,520 --> 00:05:14,080
 your front armhole measurement in your cap height,

97
00:05:14,080 --> 00:05:15,600
 then the bicep is what it is.

98
00:05:15,600 --> 00:05:19,600
 In this case, if your bicep was smaller than this measurement,

99
00:05:19,600 --> 00:05:22,000
 you would just have to have extra ease in your bicep.

100
00:05:22,000 --> 00:05:24,560
 If your bicep was larger than this,

101
00:05:24,560 --> 00:05:25,920
 then you'd have to make the adjustment

102
00:05:25,920 --> 00:05:27,680
 to the back and front armholes,

103
00:05:27,680 --> 00:05:29,920
 and you'd end up with more ease in the sleeve cap

104
00:05:29,920 --> 00:05:32,240
 than is ideal and you'd have to put in gathers

105
00:05:32,240 --> 00:05:33,920
 or a dart in the cap.

106
00:05:33,920 --> 00:05:36,800
 Now just a final note about the ideal amount of ease

107
00:05:36,800 --> 00:05:39,200
 that you want in the sleeve cap to be able to ease it

108
00:05:39,200 --> 00:05:40,240
 into the armhole.

109
00:05:40,240 --> 00:05:43,040
 Most pattern making books I've referred to

110
00:05:43,040 --> 00:05:45,360
 say that you need between one and a quarter

111
00:05:45,360 --> 00:05:48,400
 and one and three quarter inches ease in the sleeve cap.

112
00:05:48,400 --> 00:05:50,640
 But many fitting books I've read,

113
00:05:50,640 --> 00:05:52,560
 written by dressmakers or solers,

114
00:05:52,560 --> 00:05:55,040
 say that three quarters of an inch is sufficient

115
00:05:55,040 --> 00:05:56,960
 and one inch is the maximum.

116
00:05:56,960 --> 00:05:59,360
 So it seems pattern makers say more

117
00:05:59,360 --> 00:06:01,680
 and dressmakers seem to think a little less.

118
00:06:01,680 --> 00:06:04,320
 Now just a couple more notes before we start drafting the sleeve.

119
00:06:04,800 --> 00:06:07,600
 The standard amount of ease you add to the bicep is two inches.

120
00:06:07,600 --> 00:06:10,800
 If you have the upright posture of a standard figure,

121
00:06:10,800 --> 00:06:13,440
 adding two inches ease to the bicep will help you,

122
00:06:13,440 --> 00:06:15,360
 one end up with a desirable cap height,

123
00:06:15,360 --> 00:06:17,680
 and two will also result in a comfortable sleeve.

124
00:06:17,680 --> 00:06:21,360
 Now the issue of the ease in the bicep

125
00:06:21,360 --> 00:06:24,400
 is that it's not only for bicep ease,

126
00:06:24,400 --> 00:06:26,480
 it's ease for movement as well.

127
00:06:26,480 --> 00:06:28,560
 When you stand with your arms straight down,

128
00:06:28,560 --> 00:06:30,560
 the two inches ease in the bicep might be plenty.

129
00:06:30,560 --> 00:06:33,920
 But then when you move your arms forward and up,

130
00:06:33,920 --> 00:06:37,760
 the sleeve might become constrictive, uncomfortable or even painful.

131
00:06:37,760 --> 00:06:40,560
 That's because garments behave differently with movement

132
00:06:40,560 --> 00:06:42,480
 than they do when you're standing still.

133
00:06:42,480 --> 00:06:44,640
 So depending on your body shape,

134
00:06:44,640 --> 00:06:46,560
 your posture and other issues,

135
00:06:46,560 --> 00:06:49,280
 it may mean that you need more than the standard

136
00:06:49,280 --> 00:06:51,280
 two inches ease in the bicep.

137
00:06:51,280 --> 00:06:54,240
 If sleeves and ready to wear clothing are generally

138
00:06:54,240 --> 00:06:56,720
 constrictive when you move your arms forward and up,

139
00:06:56,720 --> 00:06:59,360
 then you will probably have to add more than two inches

140
00:06:59,360 --> 00:07:00,880
 standard ease in the bicep.

141
00:07:00,880 --> 00:07:03,280
 You may need three inches, you may need more.

142
00:07:03,840 --> 00:07:06,480
 I recommend that if you find ready to wear

143
00:07:06,480 --> 00:07:09,680
 sleeves quite constrictive that you start with three inches.

144
00:07:09,680 --> 00:07:12,000
 The issue with adding the three inches instead of two

145
00:07:12,000 --> 00:07:14,560
 is that chances are you're going to end up with more ease

146
00:07:14,560 --> 00:07:16,640
 than is desirable in the sleeve cap.

147
00:07:16,640 --> 00:07:18,480
 And so you're going to end up with gathers

148
00:07:18,480 --> 00:07:20,800
 or have to put a dart in the cap.

149
00:07:20,800 --> 00:07:24,640
 So let's start drafting the sleeve.

150
00:07:24,640 --> 00:07:27,600
 Draw a horizontal line from A to B

151
00:07:27,600 --> 00:07:30,720
 that is eight inches longer than your bicep measurement.

152
00:07:30,720 --> 00:07:33,360
 Note that I'm only showing you the top of the sleeve at the moment.

153
00:07:33,360 --> 00:07:35,280
 You'll need a lot more paper below.

154
00:07:35,280 --> 00:07:38,560
 Your paper needs to be a few inches longer than the length of your sleeve.

155
00:07:38,560 --> 00:07:41,360
 In the middle of that A to B line,

156
00:07:41,360 --> 00:07:45,040
 mark point C and draw a vertical guideline at right angles

157
00:07:45,040 --> 00:07:47,760
 to the A to B line about seven inches high.

158
00:07:47,760 --> 00:07:50,800
 Add your bicep measurement plus ease.

159
00:07:50,800 --> 00:07:53,040
 The amount of ease will vary per person.

160
00:07:53,040 --> 00:07:55,040
 Two inches ease for standard figures,

161
00:07:55,040 --> 00:07:58,080
 but if sleeves and ready to wear clothing are usually constrictive,

162
00:07:58,080 --> 00:07:59,440
 start with three inches ease.

163
00:07:59,440 --> 00:08:02,960
 On the A to B line with point C at the centre,

164
00:08:03,360 --> 00:08:08,000
 measure out your bicep measurement plus ease and mark points E and F.

165
00:08:08,000 --> 00:08:13,680
 Add together your back armhole measurement plus a quarter inch ease

166
00:08:13,680 --> 00:08:18,240
 to your front armhole measurement plus a quarter inch ease,

167
00:08:18,240 --> 00:08:20,320
 then divide the total by two.

168
00:08:20,320 --> 00:08:23,440
 Using that measurement, measure from point E

169
00:08:23,440 --> 00:08:27,040
 up to touch the C to D line, mark point G.

170
00:08:27,040 --> 00:08:30,080
 Don't draw a line, you're just measuring up and marking point G.

171
00:08:31,120 --> 00:08:36,880
 Now starting at point G, take your back armhole measurement plus a quarter inch ease

172
00:08:36,880 --> 00:08:39,840
 and measure towards the A to B line.

173
00:08:39,840 --> 00:08:43,280
 If your back armhole measurement is smaller than the front,

174
00:08:43,280 --> 00:08:47,440
 you're going to end up with a point to the right of point E.

175
00:08:47,440 --> 00:08:50,880
 If your back armhole measurement is larger than your front,

176
00:08:50,880 --> 00:08:53,920
 the point will end up to the left of point E.

177
00:08:53,920 --> 00:08:57,280
 So mark that and label it point H.

178
00:08:59,600 --> 00:09:03,280
 Now using your front armhole measurement plus quarter inch ease,

179
00:09:03,280 --> 00:09:05,920
 measure from point G to touch the A to B line.

180
00:09:05,920 --> 00:09:09,440
 If your front armhole measurement is smaller than the back,

181
00:09:09,440 --> 00:09:14,000
 the point will end up as shown in the example to the left of point F.

182
00:09:14,000 --> 00:09:18,320
 If your front armhole is larger, it will end up to the right of point F.

183
00:09:18,320 --> 00:09:20,560
 Mark that new point I.

184
00:09:20,560 --> 00:09:25,840
 Your bicep line is now from point H to point I.

185
00:09:26,880 --> 00:09:32,320
 Using your body cap height measurement, measure up from point C and mark point J.

186
00:09:32,320 --> 00:09:35,920
 If G and J are the same or very, very close,

187
00:09:35,920 --> 00:09:38,960
 you won't have to do anything for this slide.

188
00:09:38,960 --> 00:09:43,600
 If your point J is below point G as an example A,

189
00:09:43,600 --> 00:09:47,120
 you will need to redraw the front and back armhole lines.

190
00:09:47,120 --> 00:09:54,320
 So maintaining their same length, measure from point J towards the A to B line

191
00:09:54,320 --> 00:09:57,360
 and mark new points H2 and I2.

192
00:09:57,360 --> 00:10:02,080
 In this case, you have increased your bicep measurement.

193
00:10:02,080 --> 00:10:05,200
 If J is above G as an example B on the right,

194
00:10:05,200 --> 00:10:11,360
 redraw your front and back armholes from J to H and from J to I.

195
00:10:11,360 --> 00:10:18,080
 In this case, an additional mount has been added on to the ease in the sleeve cap.

196
00:10:18,080 --> 00:10:22,960
 If that's a large amount, you might not be able to actually ease it into the armhole

197
00:10:22,960 --> 00:10:25,280
 and you may have to have gathers or a dart.

198
00:10:25,280 --> 00:10:33,840
 Find the center of the H to I line and mark the point at the center C2.

199
00:10:33,840 --> 00:10:36,400
 This is the center of your bicep line now.

200
00:10:36,400 --> 00:10:42,720
 Draw a vertical line down from point C2 at right angles to the bicep line.

201
00:10:42,720 --> 00:10:47,280
 The length of that line is the sleeve length minus the cap height.

202
00:10:47,840 --> 00:10:54,560
 Mark the end point K and draw a wrist guideline at right angles to the C2 to K line.

203
00:10:54,560 --> 00:10:59,760
 Using the shoulder tip to elbow measurement minus the cap height,

204
00:10:59,760 --> 00:11:04,960
 measure down from C2 on the C2 to K line and mark point L.

205
00:11:04,960 --> 00:11:11,360
 With point L at the center, draw a horizontal line at right angles to the C2 to K line.

206
00:11:11,360 --> 00:11:16,560
 The length of this line is the elbow measurement, that is bent elbow plus ease.

207
00:11:16,560 --> 00:11:20,640
 The amount of ease you will use will depend on how much ease you added to the bicep.

208
00:11:20,640 --> 00:11:26,960
 If you added two inches ease to the bicep, add one and a quarter inch ease to the elbow.

209
00:11:26,960 --> 00:11:31,680
 If you added three inches ease to the bicep, add one and three quarter inches to the elbow.

210
00:11:31,680 --> 00:11:36,320
 If you added four inches ease to the bicep, add two inches ease to the elbow.

211
00:11:36,320 --> 00:11:41,200
 This is just a note explaining why we added a proportional amount of ease to the elbow,

212
00:11:41,200 --> 00:11:44,000
 depending on the ease added to the bicep.

213
00:11:44,000 --> 00:11:46,800
 Otherwise, we might end up with a very tapered sleeve.

214
00:11:46,800 --> 00:11:51,360
 If you add a lot of ease to say the bicep and not much to the elbow, it tapers

215
00:11:51,360 --> 00:11:57,920
 and it can end up tapering down to an extreme so that you can't actually fit your hand in.

216
00:11:57,920 --> 00:12:00,080
 It is best to add proportional ease.

217
00:12:00,080 --> 00:12:04,160
 We will now draw the seam lines in.

218
00:12:04,160 --> 00:12:10,480
 Draw a line from H at the bicep passing through point M at the elbow to meet the wrist line.

219
00:12:10,480 --> 00:12:16,160
 Mark that point O. Draw another line from F through point N at the elbow

220
00:12:16,160 --> 00:12:18,720
 to touch the wrist line and mark point P.

221
00:12:18,720 --> 00:12:23,120
 Now we're going to start creating a dart at the elbow.

222
00:12:23,120 --> 00:12:29,920
 Measure out from point M on the M to N elbow line for a quarter of an inch and mark point Q.

223
00:12:29,920 --> 00:12:37,120
 Now measure down from M on the M to O line for one inch and mark point R.

224
00:12:37,120 --> 00:12:43,200
 This is the dart width. Measure five eighths of an inch from point O on the O to P wrist line

225
00:12:43,200 --> 00:12:47,280
 and mark point S. Now we're going to draw one of the dart legs.

226
00:12:47,280 --> 00:12:52,480
 Measure the distance from Q to L on the elbow line and divide that by two.

227
00:12:52,480 --> 00:12:57,920
 Using that value, measure from Q and mark the elbow point dart.

228
00:12:57,920 --> 00:13:03,760
 Draw the second dart leg, the same length as the first one, starting at the dart point

229
00:13:03,760 --> 00:13:07,280
 and going through point R and marking point T.

230
00:13:07,280 --> 00:13:13,040
 Now draw a line from H to Q. Note that there may be a very slight difference

231
00:13:13,040 --> 00:13:17,520
 between the length of this line to the length of F to N,

232
00:13:17,520 --> 00:13:20,880
 but it will be very very minimal and it can be eased when stolen.

233
00:13:20,880 --> 00:13:30,320
 Measure N to P and using that measurement, draw a line from T through point S and mark point U.

234
00:13:31,600 --> 00:13:35,520
 Just to be clear here, we will be sewing. When we sew the sleeve up,

235
00:13:35,520 --> 00:13:43,280
 we will be sewing the H to Q line to the F to N line and the T to S line to the N to P line,

236
00:13:43,280 --> 00:13:48,240
 so they need to match in length. We need to draw the wrist line from U to P.

